defaultWhether the current sanctions and penalties for tobacco smuggling are appropriatedefault17
default.
default              
defaultACS believes that current sanctions against tobacco smugglers, particularly those who operate on the ground within communities, are not strong enough and do not target the correct people. 
defaultCurrent activities, such as the use of UK Duty ‘fiscal mark’ 
defaultdetector and banning orders do no
defaultt target
default illicit traders who trade in locations such as
default vans and tab houses
default, but instead 
defaultimpose further regulatory burdens on legitimate retailers.
default18
default. 
default              
defaultIn addition to 
defaultadditional resources for Trading Standards and local police to be able to bring action against illicit tobacco traders, new and harsher penalties to deter these sellers should also be introduced. 
defaultACS believes that the current structure of sanctions is counter-pro
defaultductive and needs to be tackled.
default 
defaultCurrent
default sanctions
default are also 
defaulttoo complicated and time-consuming for HMRC to pursue. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default19
default.
default              
defaultA suite of new and easy to administer penalties targeted at sellers of smuggled tobacc
defaulto products should be introduced, including:
default20
default.
default              
defaultAlthough prosecutions for volume crime have been gradually increasing, HMRC has not set targets for the number of prosecutions for tobacco
default fraud in cases of volume crime in tobacco smuggling
default; there are targets for volume crime across all regimes, but this is not 
defaultspecific to the 
defaultsale of tobacco
default. 
defaultA clear target for the number of volume crimes for tobacco smuggling should be set in order for HMRC to be able to further increase the number of prosecutions for volume tobacco crimes and to track progress.
default 
defaultThe National Audit Office’s report also highlights that the application of civil penalties against volume crime offenders was delayed because of recruitment delays and legal considerations
default, which again hampers the progress that can be made to tackle illicit traders who operate at the heart of our communities. 
